      "writtenOn": "2026-05-07T15:37:58Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Hi @ed@tanous.net, @molberding@nvidia.com,\n\nThanks for the clear feedback. We will abandon this patch.\n\nI now understand the perf cost of boost::coroutines and agree it\u0027s the wrong tool here.\n\nFor our Reset use case, the operation typically completes within a few seconds, and we want the caller to receive 200 only after the response is available.\n\nBesides @jvoon@nvidia.com\u0027s proposed sdbusplus deferred-reply API, would the pattern used in certificate_service.hpp\u0027s GenerateCSR also be an option?\n\nThere, the daemon kicks off the work and returns the D-Bus reply immediately, while bmcweb keeps the HTTP request open by holding AsyncResp inside both a D-Bus signal subscription and a timeout. \nWhen the daemon finishes and emits the completion signal, bmcweb\u0027s signal callback fills in the response and sends 200 to the caller; if the timeout fires first, an error is returned instead.",
      "parentUuid": "b1ff7d34_21c69155",
      "revId": "cf7c959cc3ce1512ab52957fb6aa88ca8810b280",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
